{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Evicted: Poverty and Profit in the American City | title_orig = | translator = | image = Matthew Desmond at 2017 National Book Festival.jpg | border = yes | author = [[Matthew Desmond]] | illustrator = | caption = Author [[Matthew Desmond]] discusses the book at the 2017 [[National Book Festival]] | country = [[United States]] | language = English | series = | subject = [[Sociology]], [[Poverty]], [[Low-income housing]] | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[Crown Books|Crown]] | release_date = March, 2016 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]]) | pages = 432 | isbn = 978-0-553-44743-9 | dewey = | congress = | oclc = 936126297 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Evicted: Poverty and Profit in the American City''''' is a 2016 non-fiction book by the American author [[Matthew Desmond]]. Set in the poorest areas of [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], the book follows eight families [[Eviction in the United States|struggling to pay rent]] to their [[Landlord|landlords]] around the [[Financial crisis of 2007–2008|2008 financial crisis]]. It highlights the issues of [[extreme poverty]], [[affordable housing]], and economic exploitation in the United States.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/247816/evicted-by-matthew-desmond/|title=Evicted by Matthew Desmond {{!}} PenguinRandomHouse.com|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://crownpublishing.com/archives/feature/23582|title=Poverty and Profit In the American City - The Crown Publishing Group|website=crownpublishing.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref>
The book won the [[2017 Pulitzer Prize]] for [[Pulitzer Prize for General Nonfiction|General Nonfiction]]. Pulitzer committee's selected the book, "For a deeply researched exposé that showed how mass evictions after the 2008 economic crash were less a consequence than a cause of poverty."<ref name="general-non-fiction">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pulitzer.org/winners/matthew-desmond|title=''Evicted: Poverty and Profit in the American City'', by Matthew Desmond|last= The Pulitzer Committee|website=www.pulitzer.org|language=en|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref> It also won the 2016 [[National Book Critics Circle Award]], 2017 PEN/John Kenneth Galbraith Award for Nonfiction, 2017 [[Andrew Carnegie Medals for Excellence in Nonfiction|Andrew Carnegie Medals for Excellence in Nonfiction Award]], the 2017 Hillman Prize for Book Journalism, the 2017 ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' [[Heartland Prize]], and the 2018 [[Order of the Coif]] Book Award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/awards-and-prizes/article/73100-louise-erdrich-matthew-desmond-win-2016-nbcc-awards.html |title=Louise Erdrich, Matthew Desmond Win 2016 NBCC Awards |work=Publishers Weekly |author=Calvin Reid |date=March 17, 2017 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://pen.org/2017-penjohn-kenneth-galbraith-award/|title=2017 PEN/JOHN KENNETH GALBRAITH AWARD FOR NONFICTION - PEN America|date=2017-01-18|work=PEN America|access-date=2017-05-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/awardsgrants/carnegieadult|title=Andrew Carnegie Medals for Excellence in Fiction & Nonfiction {{!}} Awards & Grants|website=www.ala.org|language=en|access-date=2017-05-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hillmanfoundation.org/hillman-prizes/2017|title=2017 Hillman Prizes|work=Hillman Foundation|access-date=2017-05-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/books/ct-heartland-prize-whitehead-desmond-books-0507-20170502-story.html|title='The Underground Railroad,' 'Evicted' win Tribune's Heartland Prizes|last=Schoenberg|first=Nara|work=chicagotribune.com|date=May 4, 2017|access-date=2017-05-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orderofthecoif.org/COIF-bookaward.htm|title=Order of the Coif Book Awards|last=The Order of the Coif.|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-27}}</ref>
