'''Natalia Nikitichna Tolstaya''' ({{lang-ru|Наталья Никитична Толстая}}; May 2, 1943, [[Yelabuga]], [[Tatar ASSR]] – June 15, 2010, [[Saint Petersburg]]) was a [[Russia]]n writer and translator from the [[Tolstoy family]]. She was a granddaughter of writer [[Aleksey Nikolayevich Tolstoy|Alexei Tolstoy]] and poet [[Mikhail Lozinsky]], and sister of the writer [[Tatyana Tolstaya]]. She taught for many years at [[Saint Petersburg State University]], from which she had also graduated. Tolstaya's specialty was [[Scandinavia]]n languages, and she wrote her first stories in [[Swedish language|Swedish]] before turning to [[Russian language|Russian]]. In 2004 she was awarded the [[Order of the Polar Star]] by the Swedish government for her efforts in fostering better relations between Russia and Sweden.
