The '''Society for the History of Authorship, Reading and Publishing''' (SHARP) formed in 1991 in the United States on the initiative of scholars Jonathan Rose, Simon Eliot, and others.<ref>{{citation |author=Ian Gadd |chapter=SHARP (Society for the History of Authorship, Reading and Publishing) |isbn=9780199570140 |year=2010 |title=Oxford Companion to the Book |editor1=Michael F. Suarez |editor2= [[Henry Woudhuysen|H.R. Woudhuysen]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Center for the Book and the History of the Book |author1= Eleanor F. Shevlin |author2= Eric N. Lindquist |journal= [[Libraries & the Cultural Record]] |volume= 45 |jstor=20720639 |year=2010 }}</ref> Its members study the [[history of books]] and the "composition, mediation, reception, survival, and transformation of written communication."<ref>{{cite web |title=Sharpweb.org |url=http://www.sharpweb.org/main/ |accessdate= November 28, 2017 }}</ref> The group maintains an electronic discussion list (SHARP-L), produces the academic journal ''[[Book History (journal)|Book History]]'' (est. 1998), and holds annual meetings.<ref>{{cite journal |title=History of the Book: An Undisciplined Discipline? |author=Cyndia Susan Clegg |journal=[[Renaissance Quarterly]] |volume= 54 |doi=10.2307/1262225 |year=2001 }}</ref> Membership consists mostly of British and American scholars.
